# Bug report

## Current behavior

Currently, some toast properties critical calculations ([such as the `domIndex` calculation](https://github.com/mui/base-ui/blob/3d8adbdb1bb1db51e778a75aa972fcb668dd5d54/packages/react/src/toast/root/ToastRoot.tsx#L130)) are based on referential equality between the toast object passed to the toast root component and the ones in the internal toast context.

This makes it impossible to, among other use cases, enforce type-safety on the `data` field. This is a snippet from my `useToast` hook which wraps `Toast.useToastManager`:

```ts
export const useToast = () => {
    const toastManager = ToastPrimitive.useToastManager()

    [...]

    const list = toastManager.toasts.flatMap(toast => {
        const parsed = toastSchema.safeParse(toast.data)
        if (!parsed.success) {
            return []
        }

        // creating a new object breaks all internal toast calculations relying on referential equality
        return {
            ...toast,
            data: parsed.data,
        }
    })
}
```

## Expected behavior

The toast properties calculations should never be based on referential equality between the toast object passed as prop to the toast root component and the ones in the internal context, instead they should be based on the toast's unique identifier, which is passable to user-created objects matching the `ToastRootToastObject<unknown>` type

## Reproducible example

https://stackblitz.com/edit/vitejs-vite-twkafu6v?file=src%2FApp.tsx

## Base UI version

For example v1.1.0

## Which browser are you using?

Chrome

## Which OS are you using?

Mac OS

## Which assistive tech are you using (if applicable)?

None

## Additional context

In the StackBlitz when the button is clicked and the toast is added its ref function fires an alert with its toast index variable, it should be zero but it's minus one (i.e. not found return value of the `indexOf` array function). If the `flatMap` at line 15 is changed to not spread the toast object into a new object but just pass it on, then the added toasts exhibit the correct toast index variable

## Overview
This PR makes the hook `useToastManager` a generic function so that the returned `toasts`, `add`, `update`, and `promise` functions all inherit the type argument provided to `useToastManager`.

I thought this might be worth a discussion. For my use case (and I imagine this is true for most folks, but perhaps not), I have a single type which represents a discriminated union of all possible types that can be used as the type of `data` in toast objects. When I access the toast manager with `useToastManager`, it would be very convenient to specify this type at that time and not need to type cast when using the `toasts` on the returned toast manager.

## Example

For example, today I need to do something like the following:

```tsx
enum ToastType {
  A = 'A',
  B = 'B',
}

type CustomToastA = {
  type: ToastType.A;
  someCustomField: boolean;
  ...
};

type CustomToastB = {
  type: ToastType.B;
  someOtherField: string;
  ...
};

type CustomToast = CustomToastA | CustomToastB | ...

const MyComponent = () => {
  const { toasts } = Toast.useToastManager();
  
  return (
    <Toast.Viewport>
      {toasts.map((toast) => {
        // Need to type cast here
        const typedToastData = toast.data as CustomToast;
        ...
      })}
    </Toast.Viewport>
  );
};
```

With this change, if the type `CustomToast` were provided to `useToastManager` as a type argument in the above example, then `toast.data` would be automatically typed as `CustomToast`.

## Concerns

This change modifies `add`, `update`, and `promise` to no longer be generic. So I believe this would constitute a breaking change for those methods if consumers are currently providing type arguments to them.

